data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression-tree-building block can be replaced:

```csharp
// ✅ .NET 10 — simple lambda with conditionals
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` machinery no longer compiles because the signature changed from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Action<...>`.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Duplicate property names are now uniquified.** Since both `ShippingAddress` and `BillingAddress` have a `Street` property, EF 10 auto-appends a number (e.g. `Street1`). Pin your existing names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to column `BillingAddress_City` — it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. Pin with `HasColumnName()` to keep the old name if you don't want a migration rename:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

Without these fixes, EF will generate a migration that renames the columns.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new: redacted SQL for safe logging
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logs (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on that interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) — they all gained the same parameter.
